# 1. Understanding workgroup and domain environments 
 
- It automatically join the works-group after installation 
 - Changing workgroup to domain 
        ==>  Control panel --> system --> computer name, domain and workgroup setting. --> Change setting --> two option(Change / Network ID Wizard) --> need name of the domain and credentials.
        
# Work-Group Network Vs Domain Network:

| Work-Group                                                                                                                                         | Domain Network                                                                                                                             |
| -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Workgroup** networks are typically used in small environments, such as small offices or home networks, where each computer is a standalone unit. | **Domain** networks are used in larger environments, such as medium to large businesses, where there is a need for centralized management. |
| There is no central management; each computer manages its own user accounts and security settings.                                                 | A central server, known as a Domain Controller, manages users, devices, and security settings.                                             |
| Separate on Each Device                                                                                                                            | Single Sign-On for Domain                                                                                                                  |
| Managed Individually                                                                                                                               | Managed Centrally                                                                                                                          |
| Low Security --> Need to configure and defend each computers individually                                                                          | High security because of centralized system                                                                                                |
| Max of 20 Computers Supported                                                                                                                      | Unlimited (42 Billions)                                                                                                                    |

# 2. Active Directory Terms:
### Logical Components (Design and Planning)
- ==Domains:==
     ==> A domain is a logical group of users, computers, and other resources that share a common directory database. It provides an administrative boundary for managing resources and security.
-  ==Domains Tree:==
      ==> Parent- Child relation of the domains create domain trees or simply tree.
- ==Forest :==
      ==> A forest is a collection of one or more domain trees that share a common schema, configuration, and Global Catalog. It serves as a trust boundary where multiple domains can interact.
-  Organizational Units (OUs)
- Containers
###  Physical Components (Servers)
- Domain Controllers (It's just a database server) 
     ==> A DC is essentially a database server where the AD database is stored.
- Read-only Domain Controllers (RODC)
     ==> It is used in remote locations where security risks are higher.
### Example
Imagine a large organization with multiple locations:

- **Domains:** Each location might have its own domain, such as "East.Company.com" and "West.Company.com".
- **Domain Tree:** These domains are part of a domain tree under the root domain "Company.com".
- **Forest:** All domains within the organization are part of a single forest, sharing resources and policies.
- **OUs:** Each domain has OUs to manage departments, such as "HR," "IT," and "Finance".
- **Containers:** Each domain has predefined containers where default users and computers are stored.
- **DCs:** Each location has its own domain controller to authenticate users and computers.
- **RODCs:** Remote locations have RODCs deployed to enhance security and manage database replication.
These logical and physical components help in structuring and efficiently managing Active Directory.
